WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.400
I just want to welcome everyone to the Data Science Hangout. I know most of you have been

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:14.160
here before, but if this is your first time, it's an open space for current and aspiring

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:19.760
data science leaders to just connect and chat about some of the more human-centric questions

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:25.120
around data science leadership. We really want to create a space where everybody can

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:30.480
participate and want to hear from everyone. So there's three ways that you can ask questions.

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:37.119
You can jump in live. I can pass you the the fake microphone and put questions in the chat.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:41.919
And then we also have a Slido link where you could ask anonymous questions too.

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:45.759
And Rob will help me by sharing that in the chat window right now.

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:52.880
But this will be recorded and shared up to YouTube as well for anybody that missed it today. So just

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:57.919
want to make sure I let everybody know that. Zoom should tell you that when you're joining as well.

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:04.639
But I'm so excited to be joined by my co-host for today and friend on LinkedIn. I know we haven't

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:10.879
met yet in person, but I'd like to introduce you to Edgar Gallo, Chief Data Officer at Daimler

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:17.440
Trucks North America. Edgar, could I turn it over to you to have you introduce yourself and some of

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:23.839
the work that you do on your team? Thank you very much. Yes, absolutely. Very excited to be here. I've

00:01:23.839 --> 00:01:33.040
been attending for a few weeks now and months, I can say. Super interesting topics. I hope I

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:40.480
meet the caliber of the other co-hosts you have had. Big shoes to fill here, but over the

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:46.800
time I've learned people are very welcoming and warm. So my background, I've been with our company

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:54.000
for almost 15 years now. I started with them in finance and controlling in a very quantitative

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:04.160
like role. From there, I moved into a role where we—a team we have in our company is kind of unique

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:11.759
in that it is an internal consulting team. And what we do is we focus on process improvement,

00:02:11.759 --> 00:02:18.559
process engineering, load balancing, things of that nature. And back when I joined, we had

00:02:19.919 --> 00:02:25.440
the two areas of focus together. One of them was our area in manufacturing and our area on the

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:32.080
non-assembly space, if you will, processes like accounting and hiring, things of that nature.

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:42.080
And it was in that, let's say, play space where I did a lot of the analytics that were not so much

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:47.279
driven by my interest, but the interest of others, which was really, really key for me to

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:55.600
understand and really tag along into what back in the day with the background in econometrics and

00:02:55.679 --> 00:03:05.520
stats, I was able to recognize the data science. So I run a team of very curious and inquisitive

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:10.559
people that were split between the East Coast and the West Coast. We run projects all over the place,

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:18.160
super fun. But something I learned over time is that the ability to measure not only their

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:24.320
satisfaction with their work, as in are we moving the needle or not with all the time we're spending

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:30.399
in this analysis, but also the stakeholder satisfaction, right? Are they seeing a

00:03:30.399 --> 00:03:35.360
difference that is measurable? It was really closely connected to the ability to get data

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:42.080
from the processes. And that's where I had the aha moment where we really needed to move into more

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:48.160
data-centric focus. So I pitched it to my boss, he pitched it to their bosses, who pitched it to,

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.839
you know, there's always more bosses, but they all were receptive of the fact that

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:58.800
we really weren't adding any more headcounts. And we have spent about, I want to say the better

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:04.000
part of three months studying the need of the company, right? Doing this market research,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:09.600
internal, if you will, to where we had found a really nice gap that we could fit.

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:19.119
And also a training, let's say, the training method, what do we need to get from

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:26.480
really smart people to practicing data scientists? So those were the two outcomes of this three

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:32.239
month long process. And as a result of that, we started a team of data scientists that

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:38.640
started working for the company. And as of November of last year, I moved into the Chief

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:45.279
Data Office role. Again, that's fine, you know, doing the laundry with the data scientists,

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:52.880
I realized a pattern, and that was that for the first or the early days of our, let's say,

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:58.959
our existence, most of our projects were not so much data science projects, but

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:04.799
data engineering projects. Where's the data? How can we get it? How can we make sure it's

00:05:04.799 --> 00:05:10.320
reliable, trustable, things of that nature? So that really piqued my interest into the whole

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:14.160
world of governance and access management and data management.

00:05:14.959 --> 00:05:18.239
And that's what I do now for Diamond Trucks in North America.

00:05:19.679 --> 00:05:23.920
That's awesome. Thank you so much for that introduction, Edgar. And I know you just

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:29.040
touched upon that training piece a little bit and building up that team. And I think that

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:33.200
that was something we were talking about in a LinkedIn post maybe a few months ago.

00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:39.839
But I think it'd be awesome to hear a little bit more about how you went through that process. And

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:47.119
I know you mentioned like a buddy system before, between new data scientists and existing ones.

00:05:47.839 --> 00:05:50.000
But we'd love to just dive into that a little bit.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:57.200
Yeah, absolutely. So when I was hiring for this team of consultants, I really didn't

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:05.519
focus on a specific background. I more so have always focused on, I'm infamous for making up

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:12.160
words. So I focus on team get alongness, right? So I try to get different personalities that will

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:18.399
get the best out of each other when I put them to work together. So with that in mind, I ended up

00:06:18.399 --> 00:06:27.440
with people from accounting, people from engineering, really people with real life work

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:33.920
education versus a specific degree or things of that nature. So we had a really diverse team in

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:39.359
that sense. And I noticed that was very successful for the consulting piece. So when we started

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:46.720
looking at the stacking of the data science piece, it was a little more challenging in that

00:06:48.399 --> 00:06:52.799
we have to have some rigor to the training, right? So when we were doing the research

00:06:53.440 --> 00:07:00.799
part of the pitch to set up the group, we went out and said, okay, what would it be that we

00:07:00.799 --> 00:07:07.519
needed to do from a quantitative side, but also from the soft skill side? And it really validated

00:07:07.519 --> 00:07:13.359
that we needed to continue having this introvert and extrovert balance, if you will,

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:20.000
because the extroverts were really good at explaining to others the black box, and the

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.000
introverts were really, really good at creating this black box. So that was kind of the beginning

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:33.760
of setting up the buddy system. But then really one of the, let's say, value propositions

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:41.359
for the team to be created was how do we disseminate this in a company that it's

00:07:41.359 --> 00:07:47.600
trying and trying and having really advanced engineering in some pockets, where we're

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:53.359
creating trucks that are now powered by electricity and batteries and renewables,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:59.679
trucks that can drive themselves. But on the other hand, how do we bring the rest of our company

00:08:00.399 --> 00:08:05.760
up in this layer of upskilling, right? So that portion was also a

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:12.959
value prop element where we said, look, we're not only going to create training for ourselves,

00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:18.880
we're going to find ways to disseminate this knowledge. So that was one of the pieces where

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:24.239
we said anytime we engage with a department in the business, we want to have a buddy system,

00:08:24.239 --> 00:08:30.079
we want to make sure that we start, we're the driver, and our clients are in the backseat.

00:08:30.079 --> 00:08:34.640
Eventually, they choose somebody that gets along with this and put them in the passenger side.

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:40.719
So we can start creating more proliferation of the understanding of the business knowledge and

00:08:40.719 --> 00:08:46.320
how you apply the data science techniques, until eventually we swap and they are driving the

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:49.840
project through and they see it to completion with our coaching.

00:08:51.919 --> 00:08:55.760
I like that you're using the driving analogies there from Daimler.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:04.719
So for that, I'm waiting for a few questions to come in. So I want to just dive into this a little

00:09:04.719 --> 00:09:13.520
bit more. But for that training, what did that look like? Or did you use outside tools? Or did

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:20.159
you just identify a few experts internally? So just like I make up words, I'm super thrifty.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:25.520
And I'm always trying to have the least resistance from the folks that have to approve anything I

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:33.599
pitch. Super shoestring budget. So we looked at where most people were coming from. And this is

00:09:33.599 --> 00:09:39.280
for specifically for those that were going to join the team. And most people have a certain content

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:46.559
of playing along with Excel and do some data mining. So we focus on what most people know now.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:56.000
And then we focus on actually the Coursera data science certification. So we took that as the

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:01.359
backbone of our training. And then we just did this little spider chart to see how far people

00:10:01.359 --> 00:10:08.400
were away from it. And once we knew what were the primary targets of training, we looked at either

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:19.520
partnering with Coursera, or LinkedIn Learning, or a couple of other places where we have some

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:26.799
corporate licenses and affiliations. We ended up working with a company, I think, out of the UK.

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:36.960
And they had really specific training for things we wanted to learn how to use like

00:10:37.039 --> 00:10:43.200
Alteryx designer, Alteryx server, you know, statistics, things along that nature,

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:47.919
but they were all web consumed. And we managed to get a great deal through our

00:10:47.919 --> 00:10:53.280
indirect procurement team that did wonderful negotiation for us. And that was not only for us,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.960
but we were able to negotiate licenses for those that were joining us in projects from the business.

00:10:59.919 --> 00:11:05.919
Great, thank you. I see a few questions coming in around some of the work that your team's doing.

00:11:05.919 --> 00:11:11.520
And I think it's also awesome to get this feedback on or to understand like the kinds of problems

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:17.520
that your team is solving. And one is at Daimler Trucks, North America, how do you approach service

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:23.760
customer retention? So trucks going to their maintenance inspections from a data science

00:11:23.919 --> 00:11:30.640
perspective? That's a very interesting point. I think we're trying two things, right? We're

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:36.159
trying to evaluate, and this is kind of an interesting quandary, because we make the trucks

00:11:36.719 --> 00:11:43.119
and our partner dealer base sells the trucks. So every dealer is their own business, right? We

00:11:43.119 --> 00:11:48.000
don't own all those dealers. It's like, you hear about Ford of this and Ford of that, and you know,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:53.760
they're all local businesses. So while you can suggest them best practices, you can't impose

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:59.119
how they're going to conduct the business. So a lot of what we do is partner with them to develop

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:05.440
technology, to develop best practices, just like we have for internally, we have a team that goes

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:11.200
out there and helps them with assessments and finds the opportunities. But then what we do with

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:17.520
the technology piece is we're working on best methods to identify what's wrong with the truck

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:23.039
ahead of time, for example, right? Predictive maintenance, things about nature. So we have a

00:12:23.039 --> 00:12:30.559
team of data scientists that works under the big data group that is working on, you know,

00:12:30.559 --> 00:12:37.280
developing these algorithms that can help any person that manages, you know, thousands of trucks

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:43.359
to know how to best choose a location for service, you know, find out if that location has

00:12:43.359 --> 00:12:51.919
already the parts that are needed. We're even looking at some quite futuristic aspects of

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:58.239
how can the truck broker this whole thing on its own without intervention from a human. And all of

00:12:58.239 --> 00:13:02.640
that is hinging on the right algorithms, the trust with the customer, the trust with the

00:13:02.799 --> 00:13:07.760
human. And all of that is hinging on the right algorithms, the trust with the customer,

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:15.520
the right data set and the right data governance on. I wish I could share a lot more. Some of the

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:21.919
things, you know, are kind of edge on how it works and what will work. But in the whole thing is

00:13:23.119 --> 00:13:27.440
a dealer has base and they need to use this base as rapidly as they can.

00:13:28.239 --> 00:13:34.799
So anything we can do to expedite what goes into the bay to be ready to be diagnosed 100%

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:39.440
and parts being there and get it out of the bay as soon as it can.

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:44.159
It's no different than the pursuit of an F1 pit stop. Fast, fast, fast.

00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:52.479
And just let us know if there's any questions that you can't answer too. But the next one

00:13:52.479 --> 00:13:57.440
that someone asked anonymously was, have you used data science for truck configurations,

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:02.159
like the load? It's a fascinating topic. It's a fascinating topic.

00:14:03.919 --> 00:14:10.320
I haven't, but I know that we're looking at how do we make that easier? The biggest challenge

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:16.960
with our business is that we don't make trucks like cars are made in that you have a black one

00:14:16.960 --> 00:14:22.640
and a blue one and they change very little between one and the other. Really trucks are

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:30.239
completely different. Trucks are made from two frame rails and then you start bolting cross

00:14:30.239 --> 00:14:35.919
members and then you measure where you want your axles and all of these measurements create very

00:14:35.919 --> 00:14:43.919
unique, very particular specific trucks. And the one that follows it, it's not done because there's

00:14:43.919 --> 00:14:50.239
a hundred of them that are, should be made the same. It's mostly a balancing of the factory and

00:14:50.239 --> 00:14:57.119
customer requirements and when they need it. So while we have tried that and we are doing that,

00:14:57.919 --> 00:15:06.320
it's really ultimately in my opinion, it's really ultimately a balancing act between the art of

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:12.799
building a truck and designing and specing, which our partners have a huge deal of pride.

00:15:13.919 --> 00:15:19.840
On building the truck for their customers that seem right there with them and trying to make more

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:27.200
kind of vanilla packaging of trucks. So it can be, it can be kind of, it's a difficult thing to

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:32.000
balance. I want to say, well, while you can have everything pushed automatically and just say,

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.320
I want a blue, like I was playing earlier with a configuration for a Maverick. I don't know why,

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:44.239
but I really want one. Even that the permutations are small and I can just only imagine what would

00:15:44.239 --> 00:15:50.799
it take me to build a truck that I could move the axles on based on formulas that we have to need

00:15:50.799 --> 00:15:56.640
for, for example, bridge weight capacity differences in Massachusetts, in Oregon,

00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:01.840
in Washington. And if the truck's going to go across basically all states at any point in time,

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:09.520
they ought to meet those. So it's kind of challenging to just say, Hey, this size fits

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:16.799
all, but there are some efforts on improving configuration in ease of use and improving,

00:16:16.799 --> 00:16:21.039
of course, you know, potentially profitability of a package versus another.

00:16:22.559 --> 00:16:28.239
Thank you. So maybe shifting gears just a little bit for a second here. I know you,

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:35.679
you mentioned that you were at Daimler for maybe about 14 years. And I'd love to just hear

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:42.479
maybe any advice that you have for growing within the organization or getting from where you,

00:16:42.479 --> 00:16:48.159
you started to chief data officer for people who are aspiring leaders on the call too.

00:16:48.799 --> 00:16:55.599
It's, it's a very interesting thing because ever since I joined, I don't know if it was about

00:16:56.400 --> 00:17:02.320
surviving, right? I joined and then the greater session hits and everything was terrible around

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:10.640
the world. So we survived and we survived by being cohesive, by helping out beyond our need,

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:16.400
right? I might've been in finance, but if a peer of mine needed help in purchasing or supply chain,

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:24.000
or, you know, we just did it. And then eventually we had a group of people come together into a

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:31.040
cross-functional team where we were reassessing every single thing from what is the impact of,

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:37.680
you know, moving printers far away. So people don't print or print double-sided everything

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:43.199
we needed to do. So we really build a really strong community of, of purpose-driven people.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:49.680
And that really kind of really just kind of stuck with me. Like if, if I continue doing

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:56.319
purpose-driven work, you know, I get exposed to more and more opportunities. Yes, it's more work.

00:17:56.319 --> 00:18:02.079
Yes, we have longer days. It, it, it, it requires some trade-offs, but in the end,

00:18:03.199 --> 00:18:09.439
you develop this street cred of, of, you know, go-to kind of people and, and, and it just kind

00:18:09.439 --> 00:18:14.880
of follows you, right? So when I moved from finance to the internal consulting group,

00:18:15.839 --> 00:18:20.079
some peers were really happy. Some managers were really happy. Some other were, no, why are you

00:18:20.079 --> 00:18:24.239
moving? What did we do? Kind of thing, right? Eventually everyone understands that you're

00:18:24.239 --> 00:18:30.880
moving to build up a career and get to know the business. But really it was about what else can

00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:39.359
I do for you sort of thing. In, in, in the balancing act between, well, now I'm a doormat versus I'm,

00:18:39.359 --> 00:18:43.439
I'm a guy that can help but not do everything for you, right? That was, that was, and those

00:18:43.439 --> 00:18:47.920
were some of my lessons learned where you're like, wait a minute, I'm the only one left.

00:18:49.199 --> 00:18:54.079
Everybody left and I was helping them and now it's my job. So I fell a couple of times,

00:18:54.079 --> 00:18:59.439
but learned quick and, and kept doing that and fine tuning the balance between I can help you

00:18:59.439 --> 00:19:06.959
versus I'll do it for you. That was recognized by my now boss, the CIO. And, and I remember when

00:19:06.959 --> 00:19:12.560
he came first, you know, about a year into it, he kept saying, when are you coming to IT? When

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:17.680
are you coming to IT? And, and eventually, you know, the role came out and I thought, you know

00:19:17.680 --> 00:19:22.560
what? I could make a difference here on, on, on when it comes to the data management and the,

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:28.319
and the, and the governance piece and, and implementing our policy. So I took a swing

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:35.920
and I got the job. That's great. Thank you. And when you talk about that time where you were just

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:40.400
answering all these questions and just kind of helping out any team, how did you

00:19:41.359 --> 00:19:46.160
kind of come up with what were the questions that people had out of the, from the business,

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:51.680
or how did you collect those? So I don't know, maybe it's the ESL thing, right? I always double

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:57.040
check what I'm understanding. And, and I, and I asked, do you mean this or you mean that? Or

00:19:58.160 --> 00:20:02.319
instead of, I heard somebody say the other really, really well, instead of just giving them

00:20:03.520 --> 00:20:09.119
what they're asking for, ask what they're trying to answer, right? Because sometimes they come to

00:20:09.119 --> 00:20:13.599
you and say, Hey, can you give me the ROI on, on moving this supplier from here to there?

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:19.199
And you can just give them that or find out that more contextually, what are they pursuing?

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:26.079
If they're pursuing an answer to, you know, either increase, increase profitability or

00:20:26.079 --> 00:20:31.439
reduce costs, or just flat out make a decision for a purchasing agent or things like that.

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:37.040
Maybe just scratching a little bit past the surface and understand contextually.

00:20:40.079 --> 00:20:45.599
Thank you. That's really helpful. And I got that scary signal of internet unstable. So

00:20:45.599 --> 00:20:52.000
please let me know if anything happens. Tori, I see you just asked a question in the chat. If

00:20:52.000 --> 00:21:00.239
you'd want to ask that live too. Oh, sure. Hey, Edgar. I heard that you said that you report to

00:21:00.239 --> 00:21:07.359
the CIO. Yeah. And I was interested in your thoughts about data being within it versus

00:21:07.359 --> 00:21:14.160
I've seen a trend of taking the chief data officer and making it its own, like making that

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:19.359
area its own reports to the CEO. I was just curious what your thoughts are, where you think that's

00:21:19.359 --> 00:21:25.040
going and how it's worked for pros and cons. I think, yes, I've seen the same. And it's,

00:21:26.479 --> 00:21:34.319
it's an interesting path in that. I think it's a spectrum of maturity, right? And I tell you,

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:37.760
we're a very traditional business. We're an industrial.

00:21:39.359 --> 00:21:47.520
Our focus has been on making the best trucks, the most reliable trucks forever. We have an

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:54.400
extremely smart group of engineers that can do calculations over and over and over. But I think

00:21:54.400 --> 00:22:02.239
we're finally getting into understanding that those calculations eventually, you know, let's

00:22:02.239 --> 00:22:08.000
say fill the bin and they need to go somewhere, but they can't just go away because our trucks

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:14.000
last a long time. So we have a commitment to our customers. And when we're troubleshooting a truck

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:21.359
that 10, 15, 20 years old, those calculations matter. So now we're slowly creeping into the

00:22:21.359 --> 00:22:29.359
data management topic, right? Which forever has been in IT. But the cool thing about it is that

00:22:29.359 --> 00:22:41.359
my boss is not traditional IT CIO. He's a CIO that is proactive. Let's say a business maker,

00:22:41.359 --> 00:22:47.439
if you will, in that he understands that for the longest time, the accumulation of data is a good

00:22:47.439 --> 00:22:51.680
thing if you know how to use it, or it's a bad thing if you don't know how to take care of it

00:22:51.680 --> 00:22:59.119
and curate it. So I would say at the moment for the maturity spectrum and where we are as a company,

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:07.280
it's working really well for us because his understanding of IT is leading edge, I would say.

00:23:07.280 --> 00:23:17.359
So he's a really good broker of support with our board. Now, I know that as the board understands

00:23:17.359 --> 00:23:24.479
more and more about the risks and the benefits, then we talk about ransomware and the risks and,

00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:30.319
information security and information access management. And then we have more and more,

00:23:30.319 --> 00:23:35.439
let's say, regulations and right to repair, CCPA, and you name it, right?

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:46.239
Those topics are taking kind of a space of their own. And that's where with the CIO's support on

00:23:46.239 --> 00:23:54.880
it, the board realizes more and more that the CDO, it's an important role in that somebody's

00:23:54.880 --> 00:24:00.239
got to be doing traffic control beyond the business that we traditionally support,

00:24:00.880 --> 00:24:04.959
beyond the design, beyond the improvement, beyond the innovation on the product.

00:24:05.920 --> 00:24:11.680
So I don't know if I see a future for us in which the CDO would report directly to the CEO,

00:24:12.479 --> 00:24:19.119
but definitely I see a much more ingrained and deeply rooted relationship.

00:24:21.119 --> 00:24:23.520
And I hope that answers your question, if I kind of went on and on.

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:28.640
Yeah, that was, no, that was really interesting. One other question I have, oh, you have other

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:34.959
questions. Well, I'll ask this and if you have time. I've seen also, it's been interesting that

00:24:35.119 --> 00:24:43.040
interesting that not everybody understands data science and data and the structure of how do you,

00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:50.079
what do you think of, like the CDO, is it, is the CDO in that office over everything data,

00:24:50.079 --> 00:24:56.560
including data governance and modeling? And like there, it's a big area and it's explosive.

00:24:56.560 --> 00:25:02.880
So how do you handle a good structure to allow that stuff to work cohesively?

00:25:03.760 --> 00:25:10.000
So I think most people give answers related to how many people you have, what type of people you

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:17.439
have. The people topic is incredibly challenging right now. So I was very fortunate to hire

00:25:17.439 --> 00:25:23.439
real good people, you know, when I had postings, but I hear my peers over and over, you know,

00:25:23.439 --> 00:25:30.800
losing people, people moving, this and that. So the best way to tackle this at the moment,

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:35.359
it's just kind of being Johnny on the spot where it's a, whether it's a formal conversation or it's

00:25:35.359 --> 00:25:42.160
an informal conversation, right? I remember we were working on onboarding a team of external

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:46.800
providers and they were deploying this software. And I was just there because somebody thought,

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:53.199
oh, maybe, you know, knucklehead needs to be here. So Adam, so they start pitching all this stuff

00:25:53.199 --> 00:25:59.760
about AI and this and that and the other. So I go, Hey, for instance, I love your AI approach.

00:25:59.760 --> 00:26:03.839
And I love that you say it's going to like flip it over and make it work. And it's going to be

00:26:03.839 --> 00:26:09.119
done by itself. But you're talking about an application that's really close to an NLP

00:26:09.119 --> 00:26:14.079
application, which is only as good as your dictionary. So how long is it going to take

00:26:14.079 --> 00:26:18.959
you to get the dictionary gone? And then the meeting is really quiet. Like, why are you asking

00:26:18.959 --> 00:26:22.560
those questions? Well, because I have the background, I don't know what I'm doing here,

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:28.560
but I'm contributing. So that's exactly kind of you make a name for the office, if you will.

00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:37.040
As to why do we need to bring them in? And then once you get that value spread out,

00:26:37.040 --> 00:26:42.479
you will have at least having you there, then people will start coming more and more at you

00:26:42.479 --> 00:26:49.199
for those topics, whether you have the formal or the moral responsibility over those topics.

00:26:50.319 --> 00:26:53.839
So it is by contributing with some understanding and knowledge.

00:26:53.839 --> 00:27:01.280
Thank you, Edgar. And thanks, Tori, for jumping in too. I see Trevor,

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:04.319
you asked a question in the chat as well. Would you want to ask that one live?

00:27:07.839 --> 00:27:14.560
Yeah. Hi, everyone. I think my questions are self-explanatory, but I'll go ahead.

00:27:15.359 --> 00:27:21.439
So I wanted to find out a little bit more about what's your data infrastructure like?

00:27:21.439 --> 00:27:30.160
I mean, so we're talking about databases. How is all of that architecture configured?

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:38.959
You mentioned, of course, that your team, that you got some training from Coursera

00:27:38.959 --> 00:27:44.959
and this group in London. I wanted to get a little background into what sort of training that was.

00:27:45.599 --> 00:27:49.599
And I mean, the skill sets that you find most important on your team,

00:27:50.479 --> 00:27:57.520
even if they are soft skills and not necessarily data skills. And also, just to find out,

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:03.920
if your data science team, is it a centralized or is it distributed through different units

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:09.760
or departments? It's a lot. Super. Yeah. So maybe I'll start with the most fresh one and

00:28:09.760 --> 00:28:14.880
then you correct me as we go backwards. So when we started the team with the data science group,

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:23.040
it was part of this internal consulting group. So while it was centralized, it was serving

00:28:23.040 --> 00:28:30.800
the whole company. So it was deployed from our consulting group, but it was working with

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:37.839
purchasing or with aftermarket controlling or with finance, all across the board.

00:28:38.719 --> 00:28:45.520
The key there was to work widely because the purpose was also to elevate any place where we

00:28:45.520 --> 00:28:51.839
went to and bring about the knowledge and the tools and the thinking methods.

00:28:54.079 --> 00:29:00.400
So one back, I think you're talking about training. The training was very focused on the analytical

00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:05.040
tools we wanted to leverage because, again, with a shoestring budget, I didn't want to go pitch,

00:29:05.839 --> 00:29:10.400
oh, by the way, can I get this tool and that tool and that tool? There were other groups that were

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:18.800
significantly ahead of us in that they found tools like data mining tools or data aggregation tools

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:24.719
that weren't really IT per se. I mean, we're not talking a full-blown informatica solution.

00:29:24.719 --> 00:29:31.359
We're talking about something called Alteryx and Alteryx Designer. And it's really like SQL

00:29:31.359 --> 00:29:36.719
and Seras where you just drag and drop, right? Just like you could do like a shiny app.

00:29:37.839 --> 00:29:45.119
This thing helps you with that in that it just kind of does a data mining result. So this specific

00:29:45.760 --> 00:29:52.800
online software training, it wasn't really just for Alteryx, but it had a bunch of other topics,

00:29:52.800 --> 00:30:02.719
really. And I'm blanking on the name right now, but there is. So my whole inspiration from this

00:30:02.719 --> 00:30:14.400
came from a company in the UK that back in 2014, 2015, basically took Tableau and some data mining

00:30:14.400 --> 00:30:20.479
tools and created a school. I think it's called the Data School. Maybe I'm doing an ad for them

00:30:20.479 --> 00:30:28.880
here. Way, way back. And that was kind of the inspiration is like, get the data, drop in,

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:35.839
understand the business, get the data, make it stable, the data mining piece that is. And then

00:30:37.119 --> 00:30:44.560
the improvement should be made measurable via some sort of visualization tool. And not only because

00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:50.000
it's that piece of satisfaction we're looking at and for the stakeholder satisfaction as well,

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:54.880
but in that they continue to improve their processes after we're gone. So they continue

00:30:54.880 --> 00:31:01.439
to measure the improvement and see where they can take more for the benefit. So that was really kind

00:31:01.439 --> 00:31:09.599
of a foundation inspiration for us to what do we need to be learning. So this software solution

00:31:09.599 --> 00:31:16.959
vendor in the UK was a good choice for that super variety of topics. But with an accountability

00:31:16.959 --> 00:31:22.239
system that you have to take a little quiz, a little test every so often, your manager would

00:31:22.239 --> 00:31:27.520
know about it. They would keep track of what you're doing and the speed of your progress,

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:32.719
things of that nature, because the training also needs to have some sort of floor to it.

00:31:32.719 --> 00:31:41.760
Otherwise, we just hang out, which I tend to do. Architecture wise, we are a 75 year old company.

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:50.400
So you can choose the name and we have it. It was our old IT adage in that business had the budget,

00:31:50.959 --> 00:31:55.760
came to IT, asked us to get something done, and we would just get it based on what the business

00:31:55.760 --> 00:32:01.760
wanted. For that specific area, not so much holistically. So now with our new CIO, it's more

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:07.199
of a holistic view. What do we need to keep that serves every single function and what can we

00:32:07.199 --> 00:32:13.280
consolidate? So now the pursuit is that. So not that it's simplifying because as we add

00:32:13.920 --> 00:32:18.560
off-brand cloud solutions, architecture gets more complex.

00:32:20.479 --> 00:32:24.800
And I admit I forgot the very first one before architecture.

00:32:26.800 --> 00:32:28.160
That was it. That was it.

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:30.160
Oh, okay. Good. Not bad.

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:31.599
Thank you. All right.

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:37.839
Thank you, Trevor. Just a follow-up question, because it was anonymous one on Slido too,

00:32:37.839 --> 00:32:44.239
was if your team uses Python, R, or Julia, and how do you deploy data science solutions?

00:32:45.439 --> 00:32:51.439
So when I was working with the team, I was also in the middle of getting a master's in

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:57.680
data analytics. And this was an interesting combination between

00:32:57.680 --> 00:33:03.760
the School of Statistics of the university and the College of Engineering. So they both

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:10.160
combine classes. So the College of Engineering is teaching everything on Python and all the ML and

00:33:10.160 --> 00:33:20.479
AI applications. But the School of Statistics was more about hypotheses and prove it and replicate

00:33:20.640 --> 00:33:28.640
it. And we do it. So I was one foot in both. And for that reason, I was very open to the team using

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:36.319
either. So I had a team member that was really good with R markdowns and his presentations.

00:33:36.319 --> 00:33:41.920
And he was really good at conveying that to the senior leaders hiring us to work for them.

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:48.560
And another one that was just very comfortable with Python and doing some NLP applications for

00:33:49.119 --> 00:33:55.119
our HR team, for example. So we've used both. Not Julia.

00:33:57.280 --> 00:34:02.800
Thank you. Manu, I see you asked a question in the chat earlier as well. Do you want to

00:34:02.800 --> 00:34:05.199
jump in and add a little more context on that one too?

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:10.719
Yeah, sure. Hi, everybody. I wanted to ask Edgar,

00:34:11.439 --> 00:34:20.080
do you have a data science approach for the after-sales area, for the P&A area parts?

00:34:21.600 --> 00:34:31.040
Have you applied like basket analysis? Have you seen patterns in parts like collision,

00:34:31.040 --> 00:34:36.000
repair or maintenance parts? That's my question. Thank you.

00:34:36.399 --> 00:34:38.560
Thank you. Great question. I can tell you have

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:46.959
some business context. So yes, we have, like I was saying earlier, now IT has the center of

00:34:46.959 --> 00:34:53.360
excellence that has the big data group. And they have deployed some of their scientists

00:34:53.360 --> 00:34:58.479
across the aftermarket. And we have some very interesting applications in

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:09.360
part replenishment, inventory volumes. I can't really share the crown jewels deeply, but

00:35:10.399 --> 00:35:14.879
we apply to replenishment, apply to optimization of inventory levels, apply to

00:35:16.959 --> 00:35:22.159
timing of changeover. Basically, a changeover for us means we have finished the design of

00:35:22.719 --> 00:35:29.520
of either a product or a vehicle or an option in the vehicle. And we tested it,

00:35:30.399 --> 00:35:35.919
and it passes all of our testing. And then we communicate to our supply base that we need some

00:35:35.919 --> 00:35:41.040
inventory from their side, because we're going to make this now available for purchase. And that's

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:47.280
the changeover point where we say, it's no longer internal. Now it becomes an outside looking

00:35:48.080 --> 00:35:56.320
option or product. So it's time to change it over. So on that timing, we've also deployed some

00:35:56.320 --> 00:36:01.760
interesting data science applications to improve with the volume, right? If they were saying,

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:06.800
hey, get 100 of this, we're saying, well, based on our data science approach, you need

00:36:07.360 --> 00:36:10.639
twice that, but in two different locations versus just the one.

00:36:11.199 --> 00:36:17.840
With our footprint of PDCs, Power Distribution Centers, we are having some interesting

00:36:17.840 --> 00:36:23.280
applications of that as well. And some of the products that we warranty as an aftermarket

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:26.879
product as well. So yes, it's all over the place.

00:36:30.080 --> 00:36:31.360
Great. Thank you very much.

00:36:31.520 --> 00:36:38.159
I see a great question that just came in the Slido as well. And I'll just read it to you.

00:36:38.159 --> 00:36:44.399
It says, your work encompasses both low-code and code-first communities. Any ideas about how to

00:36:44.399 --> 00:36:47.679
build and encourage mutual respect between those two groups?

00:36:49.679 --> 00:36:57.040
Oof. I think the first is trust. And trust in that. First one, I would say that,

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:05.679
I was in the business, and I moved to the other side. Before I moved, we were working on low-code

00:37:06.399 --> 00:37:14.399
using OutSystems. And it was really, I was part of a bunch of different, very stressful meetings.

00:37:15.439 --> 00:37:24.000
But the last few, mostly as an observer, and where I was able to pick up that our IT counterpart,

00:37:24.080 --> 00:37:27.520
we're really stressed about something, but we were not picking up on it.

00:37:28.560 --> 00:37:34.879
And their stress was more about, hey, you guys, you really haven't seen the full picture on the

00:37:34.879 --> 00:37:42.399
other side. Hey, you guys, we haven't really made a good effort on showing you what it looks like.

00:37:42.959 --> 00:37:48.959
But when you put something out there, and you go from your development, and you pass your QA,

00:37:48.959 --> 00:37:54.239
and you go from your development, and you pass your QA, and you put it in production,

00:37:55.120 --> 00:38:01.600
it's on us. And we want to know how much of your low-code application are you willing to support

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:07.120
Saturdays and Sundays versus how much is on us. And then we just start kind of like

00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:11.120
peeling the onion and understanding really what was driving their stressors, right?

00:38:11.120 --> 00:38:16.719
The guys that are working on full-blown development piece, they know all those

00:38:16.719 --> 00:38:20.800
pitfalls. And they know they're going to be on call. And they know they don't have the luxuries

00:38:20.800 --> 00:38:27.439
of the analytic teams that just go off on the weekends as well with all their stakeholders

00:38:28.479 --> 00:38:34.879
and come back and deal with issues on Monday. So there was a lot of discovery and empathy built

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:43.040
seeking to learn what we didn't know. So from low-code, you're moving boxes here and there,

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:47.840
deploying, yeah, you make something faster, automatic, and you get pat on the back.

00:38:47.840 --> 00:38:53.520
But that requires a server. That requires information classification. That requires

00:38:53.520 --> 00:38:58.479
security around it. That requires a bunch of stuff from the infrastructure side and the software

00:38:58.479 --> 00:39:03.679
version side. And a few of the things that we really didn't know about. And not because we

00:39:03.679 --> 00:39:09.840
didn't want to, but just because we didn't really have the foresight to ask, what's driving your

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:14.639
stress? What am I doing that's stressing you? So the moment we started doing that,

00:39:14.639 --> 00:39:25.360
we started building bridges and trust and taking advice better. I hope that answers the question.

00:39:27.520 --> 00:39:35.439
Thank you. What do you think were like the first initial questions that led the team to say like,

00:39:35.439 --> 00:39:41.600
OK, now it's time to build a data science team or business problems they wanted to solve?

00:39:42.479 --> 00:39:48.320
We identified things like, say, we're looking at improving a process between two

00:39:50.239 --> 00:39:58.320
key stakeholders in the company. And the stakeholder that hired us had more data.

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:02.879
And the data was 100% pointing at the other stakeholder being at fault,

00:40:03.679 --> 00:40:09.679
right? So we started going after, well, why can I have more of this data? Why can I do my own

00:40:09.679 --> 00:40:15.760
measurements? Can I get more of this? Can I get more of that? And having that unilateral

00:40:16.879 --> 00:40:24.399
data push on you to make things happen, it was really what the driver was. How do we do this?

00:40:24.399 --> 00:40:31.840
How can we take really a data-driven approach and not so much a which stakeholder is more prepared

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:38.719
approach? And those were some of the kind of, I would say, failure modes, right? When you're

00:40:38.719 --> 00:40:45.520
trying to help the company but only one stakeholder is benefiting from your process improvement,

00:40:45.520 --> 00:40:52.000
from your analytics, it really makes no sense when you think as a system, right? As a system,

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:55.360
the imbalance can come from either side, not just from the side with data.

00:40:56.239 --> 00:41:02.719
So that really drove us to think, how do we create a team that can do this data-based decision-making?

00:41:06.479 --> 00:41:12.800
And what does your data science team look like today? Is it made up of, or I guess,

00:41:12.800 --> 00:41:15.439
how many data scientists versus data analysts?

00:41:16.479 --> 00:41:22.560
So my data science team, I think all but one have turned over into the business.

00:41:25.600 --> 00:41:31.600
Actually, one of them moved to a different area of Daimler, into Mercedes-Benz cars.

00:41:32.159 --> 00:41:37.679
So it's kind of all in the family. But what happened is, as a result of that,

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:42.959
we had really deep and long conversations with HR. We had really deep and long conversations

00:41:42.959 --> 00:41:46.959
with other areas of the business. And they understood what they were looking for.

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:54.639
So job descriptions got better. The proliferation of copy-paste of the skill sets that we were

00:41:54.639 --> 00:42:00.719
hiring for, I see them now everywhere. So now we have data scientists in the aftermarket side,

00:42:00.719 --> 00:42:07.760
in the marketing side, in finance, for sure. And they might not be labeling themselves as

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:12.719
data scientists, but the practices and the conversations we have when we get the data

00:42:12.719 --> 00:42:17.840
community together are very much of those that have the same literacy and skill level.

00:42:20.159 --> 00:42:24.000
So now I can say we have them everywhere. They just look a little different.

00:42:25.520 --> 00:42:30.239
How do you get the data science community together? Do you have some internal group?

00:42:31.360 --> 00:42:39.120
We do. COVID ruined a few things. Among those, what we used to do every year, we call it

00:42:39.120 --> 00:42:45.919
DTNA. That's the acronym for the company, DTNA Data Day. And purposely, it's never been a day.

00:42:45.919 --> 00:42:51.199
It's always been two days. And everyone's thrown off because they're highly quantitative.

00:42:51.679 --> 00:42:55.840
And they're like, it's data day, but it's two days. And then that's the conversation started.

00:42:55.840 --> 00:43:02.959
But we used to get everyone together. And my team was the driver of it. And we would get speakers.

00:43:04.479 --> 00:43:09.840
But then we would be all over the company connected with people and finding what is

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:14.239
something that you want to tackle. You want to work in session? You want to proliferate

00:43:14.239 --> 00:43:20.239
knowledge in your area? What can we do to assemble interesting topics? So we would do that.

00:43:22.159 --> 00:43:28.639
Nowadays, with one of my responsibilities being the corporate data catalog, we change a lot on

00:43:28.639 --> 00:43:35.439
our data stewards community. I have a couple of things I believe in, like having the latest and

00:43:35.439 --> 00:43:40.879
greatest version of our software, deploying benefits and improvements and things like that.

00:43:40.879 --> 00:43:48.000
So those are drivers for me to keep the community alive and growing and using the data catalog as

00:43:48.080 --> 00:43:53.280
we aspire it to be. So that's another forum where we get not only the data scientists,

00:43:53.280 --> 00:44:01.439
but the data thirsty, let's say. And what is the data catalog again?

00:44:01.439 --> 00:44:06.159
It's the brand. I don't know if I should say the brand or not. But imagine that you have

00:44:06.719 --> 00:44:12.639
Brazilian databases and schemas and all this stuff, right? So when you're trying to

00:44:13.600 --> 00:44:24.479
deploy your RStudio into a database with the ODBC, you kind of want to know what's in it.

00:44:25.439 --> 00:44:31.040
And instead of just going in there and trying to read all these columns and get samples of all

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:37.199
this data, you can go to the catalog. And the catalog is a mix between maybe I'm dating myself,

00:44:37.199 --> 00:44:42.959
but the yellow pages and Yelp, right? It's structured, organized, it has content,

00:44:42.959 --> 00:44:49.360
but it also has recommendations because over time data gets copied or federated or what have you.

00:44:52.159 --> 00:44:58.159
For your use case, you might be looking for a specific transformation of the data. And if it's

00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:04.800
